div3.sourceNote:
TC-JC [JCH], 23 March 1850. MS: Huntington. Hitherto unpbd. John Chapman (1821–94; 
                          ODNB), publisher and physician; agent for American publishers. The letter follows TC to [CRO?], 22 March 1850
, about the arrangement Chapman had made with Phillips, Sampson, & Co., and asking for pamphlet no. 3. John Chapman had no connection with Chapman & Hall, the publishers of Latter-Day Pamphlets in Britain. [This letter, pbd. at CL 44:227, is now placed at its proper chronological location.]

docBody.p:
I have not heard Mr MaccallWilliam Maccall, writer and public speaker, known to TC since; see 23:89TC to WM, 5 Aug. 1848. lecture; but have read various Pieces of his writing, and have often had the pleasure of conversing with him; and can very freely testify that he is a man of original, penetrating and accomplished mind, who has read, observed and reflected much, and with an earnestness, sincerity, and sharpness of vision which are very uncommon in our epoch. A man of elevated, devout and manful character; who, for his years, has had many experiences in this world, and has generally conquered these, and not been conquered by them;
Maccall had a varied career, starting in the dragoons, and then becoming involved with various churches, finally embracing Unitarianism, moving to London in 1846, and supporting himself and his family by preaching and writing.
 —whose conclusions, whether they differ from the common or agree with the common, are emphatically his own and well worthy of consideration.
